history.content:
I think most schedules are "doable," but it 100% depends on the kind of person you are (how you study/learn) and your time management. But, here's a couple of things (I'm not saying these things to intimidate/scare; they're just raw facts):

189 is the most workload-heavy CS upper div. (according to CS advisors), and 61C is one of the highest lower div. workloads out of all Cal classes. According to friends who took 127, 127 problem sets can be either "average," or take hours and hours (apparently you can think of 127 as "applied linear algebra/vector calculus" class). According to Prof. Sahai, EECS 127 can be seen as a level 4.5 or 5 class (out of 5, I'm assuming), and CS 189 as a level 5 (for comparison, he considers 170 to be level 4).

Would I personally do that schedule? No. But, that's because I know the kind of learner I am. So, I'd consider the things I said above, and put it into context with the kind of studier/learner you are, and decide from there :).

children.subject: Obviously any scale of difficulty will be somewhat subjective. Sahai knows a lot about these courses so his opinion is valuable. Not sure what your point is?
In my experience, 127 has been significantly harder than 189, which was significantly harder than 170. Taking 127 and 189 together is rough but doable.

"According to Prof. Sahai, EECS 127 can be seen as a level 4.5 or 5 class (out of 5, I'm assuming), and CS 189 as a level 5 (for comparison, he considers 170 to be level 4)."

Isn't this a completely random, arbitrary scale Professor Sahai came up with?

history.content: Doable or will I die? I've already taken 126 for 189-prep, for reference.
